    • Field Detail

      • OBJECT_REFERENCE_IDENTIFIER

        public static final java.lang.String OBJECT_REFERENCE_IDENTIFIER
        Identifier for the calling object of a method call.

        For example: 
         person.getName();
        "person" is the calling object, so this translates to the following in C: 
         person->getName(person);
        And this means that the method header in C must include a Person type as the first parameter for the getName() method. Therefore, the method header looks like this: 
         static String getName(Person __o__);
        And "__o__" is the chosen OBJECT_REFERENCE_IDENTIFIER.
        See Also:
        Constant Field Values

      • getParameterNode

        public ParameterNode getParameterNode(java.lang.String parameterName)
        Get the ParameterNode with the given name.

        For example: 
         public Person getPerson(String name, int age)
        Calling getParameter("name") on the Parameter list above would return the 'String name' ParameterNode.
        Parameters:
        parameterName - The name of the parameter to find.
        Returns:
        The ParameterNode with the given name.

      • getParameterNode

        public ParameterNode getParameterNode(int parameterIndex)
        Get the ParameterNode that the given index represents. The parameters are ordered from left to right, 0 being the first.

        For example: 
         public void run(int a, int b, int c)
 {
        ...
 }
        If you were to call getParameterNode(2) on the method above, you would receive the c ParameterNode.
        Parameters:
        parameterIndex - The index parameter to get.
        Returns:
        The ParameterNode at the given index.

      • getParameterOffset

        public int getParameterOffset()
        Get the offset used to access the 'visible' data of the method. For example, external methods do not have any extra parameters such as 'this' and 'exceptionData' to deal with, so 0 is returned. However, if it is an instance method, 2 is returned because the formerly mentioned parameters are present.
        Returns:
        The offset to search the parameters at.
